                <h2 id="heading-2027">The Journey Deepens: 2027</h2>
                <div class="phase">
                    <div class="phase-header">
                        <div>
                            <h3>Winter 2026/2027: Immersion, Reflection, and Grand Ideas</h3>
                            <span class="phase-date">Mid Dec 2026 - Feb 2027</span>
                        </div>
                        <button class="toggle-theme-btn" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="thematic-trace-w-2627">Show Themes ✨</button>
                    </div>
                    <div id="thematic-trace-w-2627" class="thematic-trace">
                        <h4>Thematic Tracing:</h4>
                        <p><strong>Urban Fantasy Epics, Profound Afrofuturism, and Hopeful Visions:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Great Cities Duology: Urban fantasy epic where NYC boroughs become sentient, exploring identity, community, and gentrification.</li>
                            <li>Who Fears Death: Powerful Afrofuturist novel set in post-apocalyptic Africa, dealing with magic, destiny, and identity.</li>
                            <li>Remote Control: Poetic Afrofuturist fable about a girl adopted by Death, exploring fear and connection.</li>
                            <li>The Inheritance of Orquídea Divina: Latinx magical realism weaving family secrets, curses, and hidden histories.</li>
                            <li>Lone Women: Black horror/historical Western set in 1915 Montana, focusing on secrets and isolation.</li>
                            <li>Glass and Gardens: Solarpunk Winters: Optimistic visions of sustainable futures with a winter theme.</li>
                             <li>Walkaway: Grand sociopolitical sci-fi exploring post-scarcity, open-source communities, and technological immortality.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p><em>Significance:</em> This winter phase offers immersive urban fantasy, profound Afrofuturist works for deep contemplation, unique cultural narratives, and hopeful Solarpunk visions, culminating in a big-ideas multicast experience.</p>
                    </div>
                     <article class="event-block">
